{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643039"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:48:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:48:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17981"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17981"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0,0.06,0.06,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77643"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10695"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17981"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63156"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"11219"},{"type":"tags","id":"11657"},{"type":"tags","id":"12454"},{"type":"tags","id":"12455"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24909"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32609"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77643"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is true regarding alcohol metabolism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The rate-limiting step is converting acetaldehyde to acetate","The enzyme in the rate-limiting step of alcohol metabolism is saturated after two drinks","Ethanol metabolism follows first-order kinetics","Ethanol oxidation takes precedence over the oxidation of other nutrients","The rate-limiting step is the conversion of ethanol to acetaldehyde"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct statement is that the \u003Cstrong\u003Erate-limiting step is the conversion of ethanol to acetaldehyde\u003C/strong\u003E. This step is catalysed by the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase. At high ethanol concentrations, this enzyme becomes saturated, leading to zero-order kinetics where the rate of metabolism is constant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe rate-limiting step is converting acetaldehyde to acetate\u003C/strong\u003E - This step is catalysed by aldehyde dehydrogenase and is not the rate-limiting step\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe enzyme in the rate-limiting step of alcohol metabolism is saturated after two drinks\u003C/strong\u003E - Saturation depends on individual factors and the amount of alcohol consumed\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEthanol metabolism follows first-order kinetics\u003C/strong\u003E - It follows zero-order kinetics at high concentrations\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEthanol oxidation takes precedence over the oxidation of other nutrients\u003C/strong\u003E - While ethanol is preferentially metabolised, this statement is not specific to the rate-limiting step\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ethanol metabolism primarily occurs in the liver and involves two main enzymes: alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase.","The rate-limiting step in alcohol metabolism is the conversion of ethanol to acetaldehyde by alcohol dehydrogenase.","Ethanol metabolism follows zero-order kinetics, meaning the rate is constant and independent of ethanol concentration at high levels."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Omiecinski CJ, Vanden Heuvel JP, Perdew GH, Peters JM. Xenobiotic metabolism, disposition, and regulation by receptors: from biochemical phenomenon to predictors of major toxicities. Toxicol Sci. 2011 Mar;120 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S49-75. doi: 10.1093/toxsci/kfq338. Epub 2010 Nov 8. PMID: 21059794; PMCID: PMC3145385","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63156"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17981"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63156"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:57:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T00:06:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10695"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77643"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relatio